the 2012 military coup The Military coup in 2011 came following months of popular frustration over government corruption and a demanding series of protests. Mali’s artifact-rich National Museum is known for its display of a chronological collection of Mali’s history. It is worth visiting the museum to see the Rosetta stone-like inscribed stones, the golden plaque of the Sun, various statues and sculptures made of brass. The museum is fully decorated by wood and plaster made work from the Seventeenth Century which gives the museum an authentic symmetry. The museum’s doors and door frames are made of light and dark wood panels symbolizing the desert plains and the river valley.

The most significant event in Bengueter (Njemarks) is the 1318 historical siege on Fortaleza , (kingdom now called Sudan) after a long series of negotiations and military preparations. Archival silhouettes of the patriots and their leader Toki Bojang are stored in the museum. You will also find Archeological finds, pottery tools, jewelry and documents from the Tanwol war that saw a peaceful solution and trade between Tamoumort and Njemarks at the Megarga region. So the museum is a safe Keystone to visit with a guide to the 2012 Ajani village and Calabash Demba Palace .
